% Goal
Write the `pdd/ci_validation.py` module.

% Role & Scope
Module providing CI polling, log retrieval, and fix-iteration loop infrastructure for post-push CI validation. This module bridges the gap between external CI systems (GitHub Actions, Cloud Build) and the agentic fix workflow by detecting failures, retrieving logs, and invoking an LLM to apply fixes.

% Requirements
1. Function: `run_ci_validation_loop(cwd: Path, repo_owner: str, repo_name: str, issue_number: int, max_retries: int, step_template: str, run_agentic_task_fn: Callable, timeout: float, quiet: bool, expected_head_sha_override: Optional[str] = None) -> Tuple[bool, str, float]` â€” returns (ci_passed, message, cost). When `expected_head_sha_override` is not provided, read the PR's live head SHA with `_get_pr_head_sha(...)` and use that as the expected poll head, falling back to `_get_head_sha(cwd)` only if GitHub cannot report the live head. This prevents stale cloud worktree HEADs from forcing the poll to wait for an obsolete SHA. When `expected_head_sha_override` is provided, the inner poll uses it as the expected PR head SHA. This is required for the post-checkup re-validation gate, where the checkup pushes from its own worktree and `cwd`'s local HEAD is stale relative to the PR remote. If GitHub never reports the override as the live PR head, fail with an explicit stale-head diagnostic naming the expected SHA, live PR SHA, PR number, and last known checks instead of returning a generic timeout.
2. Discover the current branch's open PR and capture `pr_number` plus current head SHA; if no PR is found, return success with an informational message.
3. Poll CI status via `gh pr checks --required --json name,state,bucket,link` with structured output. Handle exit codes: 0=pass, 1=fail, 8=pending. Use the `bucket` field plus each check `state` to distinguish pass/fail/pending/manual-action states and re-query checks after each new push/SHA so the loop does not act on stale results from the previous head. A non-empty check set with a missing/unknown bucket is not pass evidence even when `gh` exits 0; fail closed instead of relying on `all([])` or exit-code fallback, except `state=ACTION_REQUIRED` remains manual-action even when its bucket is missing or malformed. If the live PR head differs from the expected head, still read the live PR checks before sleeping; terminal non-success states such as `failure`, `cancelled`, `timed_out`, or `startup_failure` must return a settled failure immediately rather than hiding behind a stale-head wait loop. `ACTION_REQUIRED` is terminal but non-repairable by code: when every non-success/non-skipped check is `ACTION_REQUIRED` and there are no pending checks, classify it as `"action_required"` instead of `"failed"` so the CI-fix LLM loop is not invoked for a manual trigger. If any pending check is present alongside `ACTION_REQUIRED`, keep polling/pending; if any real failed/cancelled/timed-out/startup-failure check is present alongside `ACTION_REQUIRED`, the real failure wins and the status is `"failed"` even if its bucket is missing or malformed.
4. Handle startup delay: wait 30s initial delay after push, then poll every 30s up to 10 minutes for checks to appear/complete. A poll timeout SPLITS into two cases by whether any required checks were actually read for the expected head: (a) INCONCLUSIVE â†’ FAIL OPEN â€” when the poll OBSERVED the required checks and they are merely pending / not-yet-completed (a NON-empty check set; commonly a manually-triggered or external check the bot structurally cannot run, e.g. a `/gcbrun`-gated build), return `(True, <best-effort note>, total_cost)`, posting a neutral best-effort PR comment (NOT a CI-failure comment) and NOT driving the fix loop. This is safe because a genuine check FAILURE returns `"failed"` from the classifier and never reaches the timeout branch, so failing open cannot mask a real failure; the fix is already committed and a pending check the bot cannot run must not retroactively hard-fail an otherwise-correct fix. For a pure settled `"action_required"` status, first look for optional root `.pddrc` CI config: `ci.manual_triggers` maps case-insensitive ACTION_REQUIRED check-name substrings to comments and wins over `ci.manual_trigger_comment` for those checks only; passed checks must not consume or suppress manual triggers. `ci.manual_trigger_comment` is the global fallback for ACTION_REQUIRED checks without a specific match. If trigger comments are configured for multiple observed checks, post each matching trigger body at most once, waiting and repolling after each post before falling back. If no trigger remains configured, posting fails, or all configured triggers have already been posted and the checks still require action, treat the status as INCONCLUSIVE â†’ FAIL OPEN with a neutral manual-action note, because it requires an external trigger/comment and is not an actionable code failure. (b) FAIL CLOSED â€” when NO required checks were ever read for the expected head (an EMPTY check set: the PR head never matched the expected SHA, or the rollup was unreadable for the whole window), return `(False, <message>, total_cost)` and post a CI-failure comment; with no observed checks we cannot prove the checks are merely pending rather than failing, so we must not green-light a head whose real status was never seen.
5. On CI failure: retrieve failure logs via tiered fallback â€” `gh run view --log-failed` â†’ `gh api` zip download â†’ fallback to check link URL.
6. Before invoking the CI-fix LLM loop, failed checks stay fail-closed by default. Only when the root `.pddrc` has `ci.external_setup_fail_open: true`, classify clear external/manual CI setup failures from the check summary plus logs. If the logs show missing or empty GitHub Actions credentials/secrets that code changes cannot repair â€” for example `google-github-actions/auth` failing because neither `credentials_json` nor `workload_identity_provider` is configured, Firebase service-account secrets missing/unavailable, secrets unavailable for the pull-request workflow event, or GitHub integration permission failures â€” post a neutral PR note, return success with an inconclusive/best-effort message, and do NOT call `run_agentic_task_fn` or post the structured CI-failure comment, when failed check names are external/setup-shaped or generic CI/build names. Do not classify ordinary lint, import, test, or compilation failures this way; when external setup text and actionable test/lint/import/compile/build signals appear either in the logs (including common frontend build text such as `Module not found` / `Can't resolve`) or in another failed check name, the actionable failure wins and the CI-fix loop remains available.
7. On actionable failure with logs: format context and call `run_agentic_task_fn` with the step 10 LLM template to interpret and fix.
8. After fix: Only commit/push when the LLM output contains `CI_FIX_APPLIED`. Stage changed files and commit with message `"ci: fix CI failures for #{issue_number}"`, push, and re-poll.
9. Artifact Exclusion: When staging changes, explicitly exclude the same debug/intermediate artifact patterns filtered by the main orchestrator (`_fixed.py`, `.bak`, `.tmp`, `error_output*.txt`, `.pdd/` except state).
10. On max retries exhausted: return `(False, summary_of_remaining_failures, total_cost)`.
11. Function: `post_ci_failure_comment(repo_owner: str, repo_name: str, pr_number: int, failures: List[str], attempts: int, cwd: Path) -> bool` â€” posts a structured PR comment describing unresolved CI failures and what was attempted using `post_pr_comment`.
12. Function: `detect_ci_system(cwd: Path) -> str` â€” detect CI setup from repo config files (`.github/workflows/`, `cloudbuild.yaml`, etc.) for informational logging.
13. Handle the `"no_checks"` status fail-closed, not fail-open. The required-check poll returns `"no_checks"` for several distinct situations that are NOT all "this PR genuinely has no required checks": (a) the repo really has no required checks, (b) the GitHub App installation token cannot read check status ("resource not accessible by integration"), (c) `gh pr checks --required` omitted required checks that have not yet reported a status, and (d) a poll timeout where no checks were ever read. Returning ready for all of these silently green-lights a PR whose live head actually has failing checks. Therefore, before treating `"no_checks"` as ready, cross-check the live PR head's real check runs via the same REST Checks API path the final gate uses (`_poll_check_runs_for_head` / `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/commits/{head_sha}/check-runs`). Use `expected_head_sha_override` for this cross-check only when the caller explicitly supplied it as the verified head; otherwise call `_get_pr_head_sha` and use the live PR head instead of `_get_head_sha(cwd)`, because `cwd` can be stale in Cloud-run checkup/fix worktrees. Only return `(True, "No CI checks detected", total_cost)` when that REST cross-check confirms the selected head genuinely has zero check runs (true race condition / repo with no CI). If the cross-check instead finds the live head's real check runs are all passing, return ready naming the verified head â€” e.g. `(True, "Required CI checks passed on live PR head {head_sha[:8]}", total_cost)` â€” because the PR is genuinely green even though `gh pr checks --required` could not read the GraphQL `statusCheckRollup`; do NOT fall through to the failure path and drive a fix loop against an already-passing PR. If the cross-check finds any real failing or unreadable checks, fail closed â€” drive the fix loop or return `(False, summary, total_cost)`; do not treat the PR as ready. Pending / not-yet-completed checks are INCONCLUSIVE, not failing: when at least one pending check was actually observed, route to the inconclusive timeout path (item #4) and FAIL OPEN with a best-effort note rather than hard-fail an already-committed fix. Pure `ACTION_REQUIRED` check runs are also INCONCLUSIVE for the fix loop when no real failed or pending checks are present: route them to the manual-action note path (item #4), not the LLM CI-fix loop. If the cross-check is `unreadable` (it could not read the live head's check runs â€” distinct from confirming genuinely zero check runs, which returns ready as above), or if a poll `timeout` surfaced no observed checks for the expected head at all, fail closed because the head's real status is unknown. Because this cross-check reads only the REST Checks API (`commits/{head_sha}/check-runs`), it observes check runs but not legacy commit-statuses (nonâ€“check-run contexts). This distinguishes "genuinely no required checks" from "checks unreadable / not-yet-reported / failing on the live head" and from "all-passing on the live head but unreadable via the rollup".
14. Partial-check-data error handling: when `gh pr checks` exits with returncode=1, inspect stderr *before* classifying. Partial check JSON in stdout can accompany permission/config errors in stderr, so checking `latest_checks` first would mask the real error.
    - If stderr contains the GitHub "no required checks" phrase â†’ return `("no_checks", [])` immediately, even when partial check JSON was returned in stdout.
    - If stderr contains "resource not accessible by integration" â†’ log a yellow warning that the GitHub App may lack `checks:read` permission, then return `("no_checks", [])` immediately, even with partial check JSON in stdout.
    - If `latest_checks` is empty â†’ mark `saw_ambiguous_error=True`, log the stderr (yellow), and continue polling.
    - If `latest_checks` is non-empty and none of the stderr patterns above matched but stderr is non-empty â†’ log the stderr with an explicit prefix making it clear the result will be classified as failed from the exit code (e.g. `"CI polling warning (classifying as failed from exit code 1): {stderr}"`), then fall through to `_classify_check_result` so a real check failure isn't lost. Without this log, the LLM fix loop can be triggered silently when a transport error masquerades as a real failure.
15. Final gate: `run_github_checks_gate(...)` is verify-only and fail-closed. When `required_only=True`, keep using `gh pr checks --required` through the required-check poller. When `required_only=False` (the canonical `--full-suite-source github-checks` final-gate path), do not use `gh pr checks` because it reads GitHub's GraphQL `statusCheckRollup` field and can fail when an installation token has `checks:read` but not commit-status permissions. Instead poll REST check runs for the exact current PR head SHA with `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/commits/{head_sha}/check-runs?per_page=100`; do not append `--repo`, because `gh api` does not support that flag. REST API permission or transport failures must return an unreadable status, not `"no_checks"`, so callers can distinguish "zero check runs" from "could not verify check runs". Normalize check runs into the same `{name,state,bucket,link}` structure: non-`completed` statuses are `pending`; `success` is `pass`; `skipped`/`neutral` are skipped buckets; `failure`, `cancelled`, `timed_out`, and `startup_failure` are fail buckets; `action_required` is an `action_required` bucket/status; unknown completed conclusions are unknown and must fail final gate. Missing, unreadable, pending/timeout, skipped, action-required, failed, stale/wrong-head, or unknown checks all fail final gate.
16. Include `<include>context/agentic_common_example.py</include>` for `run_agentic_task` signature and `post_pr_comment` usage, and `<include>context/ci_validation_example.py</include>` for the implementation pattern.

